The paper discusses security vulnerabilities in the OpenID Connect protocol, which is used for single sign-on authentication. This falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) and software engineering (cs.SE). The paper also discusses the use of federated identity management and user authentication, which falls under the category of social and information networks (cs.SI). The attacks described in the paper involve injection payloads and exploits, which could fall under the category of cybercrime (cs.CY). Finally, the paper discusses the need to improve the OpenID Connect and OAuth specifications, which could fall under the category of programming languages (cs.PL).
